prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Standard band 7 continuum observations are employed. The choice of band 7 observations is fully described in the science case, briefly, data at longer wavelengths than the peak of the dust SED and complementary to the existing ancillary data. Band 7 is the best match to existing studies and the primary beam complements the Herschel resolution.
The requested resolution of 1 arcsec is sufficient to positionally match ALMA data to the existing imaging in COSMOS, which is the requirement for our science goals.

The requested depth of 0.4mJy/beam is required to solidly detect the galaxies at >5sigma even in cases where the Herschel 250-micron selected source is a blend of 2 to 3 galaxies. The 870 micron fluxes are predicted from fitting various SED templates (e.g. Poletta et al. 2007, Swinbank et al. 2010). The expectations from SED fitting are consistent with the flux es that are measured for the handful of sources with coincident ALMA data from ALESS (Figure 1) and HerMES IDs (Figure 2).

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The Cosmic Infrared Background peaks at ~200um and analyses of the galaxies that comprise this peak are essential to understanding galaxy evolution. Herschel-SPIRE 250um data has resolved ~20% of the CIB at this wavelength and detected >400k sources over 1000 deg^2. To unlock the full potential of these data requires well-understood associations with galaxies at other wavelengths, which is complicated by the SPIRE large beam. With ALMA we will build a gold-standard reference sample of multi-wavelength identifications for SPIRE 250um selected sources. We have a statistically complete sample of 610 sources in 1.44 deg^2 of the well-studied COSMOS field. 70% already have plausible identifications from Herschel-PACS. The remaining 30% are likely at the highest redshift. We will perform the essential band 7 ALMA continuum mapping to identify those counterparts, whilst simultaneously conducting a (ALMA-time efficient) study to confirm a representative fraction of the PACS identifications. Immediate science returns will be robust and unbiased constraints on the multiplicity functions, counts, redshift and luminosity distributions of the SPIRE sources, which are problematic to theorists.
